03945nam a22004815i 9780773597648DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735976487 a10.1515/97807735976482doi  a(DE-B1597)655332  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLC51.2.Q8b.G739 2015 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a371.02097142221 aGray, Colleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Ordinary School :bThe Study, 1915-2024 /cColleen Gray. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.) :bfull colour throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tThe Mission -- tPresentation Letter From James McDonald -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- t“Things That Really Matter” 1878–1913 -- t“A Real School” 1913–1919 -- tDays of Promise 1920–1929 -- tThe Great Depression 1930–1939 -- t“The Good War” 1939–1945 -- tA Golden Age 1946–1960 -- tA World Turned Upside Down 1960–1970 -- tA Time to Question 1970–1983 -- tA Time to Define 1983–1997 -- tState of the Art 1997–2003 -- tChallenging Times and New Horizons 2003–2014 -- tInto the Future -- tNotes on Sources -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1913, Oxford-educated Margaret Gascoigne left England for Montreal in search of new opportunities. In 1915 she established a small school for six students in the study of her downtown Montreal home - the modest but aspiring beginning of what would become known as The Study. Presenting lively images, oral testimonies, and material gleaned from the school’s archives, No Ordinary School explores the evolution of The Study through world wars, the Great Depression, the Quiet Revolution, and many stages of feminism, from its predominantly English Montreal origins into the bilingual and multicultural community that it is today. Always at the forefront of the most progressive educational developments, The Study has encouraged generations of women to transcend the boundaries of their times. Influential alumni include the physicist and Canadian Department of External Affairs civil servant Dorothy Osborne Xanthaky, avant-garde artist Marian Dale Scott, former chief curator and director of the McCord Museum of Canadian History Isabel Barclay Dobell, world-renowned architect Phyllis Lambert, internationally acclaimed pianist Janina Fialkowska, Olympic rowing medalist Andréanne Morin, and tennis star Eugenie Bouchard. Firmly grounded in a wider historical context, No Ordinary School celebrates an exceptional educational institution while paying tribute to its illustrious past and promising future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGirlsxEducationzQuébec (Province)zWestmountxHistory. 0aGirls' schoolszQuébec (Province)zWestmountxHistory. 0aPrivate schoolszQuébec (Province)zWestmountxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359764840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597648/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles